1. Minimum Age at Entry

00:13.000 --> 00:20.000
Minimum age at entry refers to the lowest age at which a person can buy a particular LIC policy.

00:20.000 --> 00:27.000
In simpler terms, it tells us the youngest age at which someone can become a policy holder.

00:27.000 --> 00:35.000
Each LIC plan has a specific minimum age requirement depending on the policy type and risk involved.

00:35.000 --> 00:47.000
For example, a child plan may allow entry as early as 0 years, but while a pension plan might require the person to be at least 18 years old.

00:48.000 --> 00:54.000
Real-world example, suppose Raj and Priya have just had a baby named Arab.

00:54.000 --> 00:59.000
They want to secure his future by investing in a child plan.

00:59.000 --> 01:06.000
LIC's new children's money back plan allows entry for children as young as 0 years.

01:06.000 --> 01:12.000
So, they can immediately purchase a policy in Arab's name.

01:12.000 --> 01:19.000
Now consider a young man named Rohan, who just turned 17 and wants to start saving early.

01:19.000 --> 01:23.000
He wants to invest in an endowment plan.

01:23.000 --> 01:28.000
However, the minimum age for that plan is 18.

01:28.000 --> 01:34.000
In this case, he will need to wait until his 18th birthday to become eligible.

01:35.000 --> 01:44.000
The rationale behind setting a minimum age is to ensure that the policy holder is of a certain age where insurability is meaningful,

01:44.000 --> 01:51.000
and in some cases, where consent and legal standing, like majority age, is important.

01:51.000 --> 01:54.000
2. Maximum age at entry

01:54.000 --> 02:02.000
Maximum age at entry is the highest age at which a person can apply for a particular life insurance plan.

02:02.000 --> 02:09.000
It is determined based on the risk appetite of the insurance company and the duration of the policy.

02:09.000 --> 02:16.000
LIC defines this limit to ensure that the person has a reasonable chance of surviving the policy term,

02:16.000 --> 02:19.000
thereby balancing risk and benefit.

02:19.000 --> 02:29.000
Real-world example, let's take the example of Mr. Sharma, who is 60 years old and is looking to buy an endowment policy.

02:29.000 --> 02:37.000
If the LIC plan he wants to buy has a maximum age at entry of 55, he won't be eligible.

02:37.000 --> 02:50.000
However, LIC offers certain pension plans or term insurance plans where the maximum entry age can go up to 65 or even 75 in some cases.

02:50.000 --> 02:55.000
This restriction protects both the policy holder and the insurer.

02:55.000 --> 03:04.000
Older individuals typically pose a higher health risk, so insurers limit entry to ensure the policy remains viable.

03:04.000 --> 03:07.000
3. Minimum sum assured

03:07.000 --> 03:17.000
Minimum sum assured is the least amount of money that LIC will pay to the nominee or policy holder in the event of death or policy maturity.

03:17.000 --> 03:22.000
This is the base coverage amount promised in the insurance contract.

03:22.000 --> 03:32.000
Each plan defines this minimum limit to make sure the cover is meaningful and justifies the administrative and underwriting costs.

03:32.000 --> 03:38.000
Real-world example, imagine Neha wants to buy a term insurance plan from LIC.

03:38.000 --> 03:44.000
The plan she is interested in has a minimum sum assured off to lakhs rupees.

03:44.000 --> 03:51.000
This means she cannot purchase that plan for a lower coverage amount like one lakh rupees.

03:51.000 --> 03:55.000
She must opt for at least to lakhs rupees.

03:55.000 --> 04:07.000
The purpose of setting a minimum sum assured is to ensure the benefit amount is sufficient for the needs it is intended to cover, such as education, marriage or death clearance.

04:07.000 --> 04:10.000
4. Maximum sum assured

04:10.000 --> 04:19.000
Maximum sum assured is the highest life cover or insurance benefit one can take under a particular policy.

04:19.000 --> 04:29.000
Some LIC plans do not have a maximum limit and allow the sum assured based on underwriting and financial capacity of the insured.

04:29.000 --> 04:41.000
Real-world example, say a businessman named Mr. Agraval wants to buy a term insurance policy to cover his business liabilities worth one crore rupees.

04:41.000 --> 04:51.000
LIC's tech term plan allows him to choose any sum assured starting from 50 lakhs rupees with no upper cap subject to income proof.

04:51.000 --> 05:01.000
Hence, if Mr. Agraval can justify his income and financial needs, he can get a cover of one crore rupees or more.

05:01.000 --> 05:08.000
High sum assured policies are beneficial for individuals with high financial responsibilities.

05:08.000 --> 05:15.000
However, they undergo strict underwriting including medical checks and financial documentation.

05:15.000 --> 05:18.000
5. Minimum policy term

05:18.000 --> 05:24.000
The policy term is the duration for which the policy will remain in force.

05:24.000 --> 05:33.000
The minimum policy term is the shortest period for which one can buy a particular LIC policy. It varies from plan to plan.

05:34.000 --> 05:39.000
Real-world example, suppose Priya wants a short term savings plan.

05:39.000 --> 05:46.000
She chooses a money back policy from LIC which has a minimum term of 20 years.

05:46.000 --> 05:54.000
If she is looking for something shorter, she might consider LIC's term plan with a 10 year term.

05:54.000 --> 06:05.000
Short policy terms are useful when the policy holder has specific short term goals such as a child's marriage in 10 years or retirement in a few years.

06:05.000 --> 06:08.000
6. Maximum policy term

06:08.000 --> 06:15.000
Maximum policy term is the longest duration for which a particular policy can remain active.

06:15.000 --> 06:23.000
This limit ensures that the policy doesn't extend beyond a practical age for maturity or risk coverage.

06:23.000 --> 06:31.000
Real-world example, let's consider a 25 year old named Suresh who wants long term life coverage.

06:31.000 --> 06:39.000
He selects LIC's Given Lab plan which allows a maximum policy term of 25 years.

06:39.000 --> 06:46.000
So, if he opts for the full term, his policy will mature when he turns 50.

06:46.000 --> 06:53.000
Some policies, like term plans, offer terms up to 40 years depending on the entry age.

06:53.000 --> 06:59.000
The longer the term, the higher the risk for LIC, which is why they have limits.

06:59.000 --> 07:06.000
It also aligns with human life expectancy and practical planning needs.

07:06.000 --> 07:09.000
7. Minimum age at maturity

07:09.000 --> 07:16.000
Minimum age at maturity is the lowest age at which the policy holder can receive maturity benefits.

07:16.000 --> 07:25.000
This ensures that the maturity payout happens only when the insured reaches a certain responsible or legally adult age.

07:25.000 --> 07:33.000
Real-world example, let's say are of parents bought a child plan when he was a newborn.

07:33.000 --> 07:38.000
The minimum maturity age under the plan is 18 years.

07:38.000 --> 07:46.000
So, even though they bought it at age 0, the earliest the benefits will be paid is when are of turns 18.

07:46.000 --> 07:53.000
This is typically aligned with age of adulthood or when financial responsibilities begin.

07:53.000 --> 08:00.000
This condition ensures that the insured has the legal capacity to handle the funds.

08:00.000 --> 08:03.000
8. Maximum age at maturity

08:03.000 --> 08:11.000
Maximum age at maturity is the oldest age at which a policy holder can receive the benefits under a policy.

08:11.000 --> 08:19.000
LIC sets this age to ensure practical viability, usually aligning with life expectancy.

08:19.000 --> 08:27.000
Real-world example, suppose Mr Kapoor, aged 50, wants to invest in a 30-year term plan.

08:27.000 --> 08:32.000
This means the policy will mature when he turns 80.

08:32.000 --> 08:40.000
If the plan has a maximum maturity age of 75, he won't be eligible for a 30-year term.

08:40.000 --> 08:46.000
Instead, he might need to opt for a shorter term like 25 years.

08:46.000 --> 08:52.000
This rule ensures that policies don't stretch beyond realistic human life spends.

08:52.000 --> 08:55.000
9. Premium Paying Term PPT

08:55.000 --> 09:02.000
Premium paying term PPT refers to the number of years the policy holder has to pay premiums.

09:02.000 --> 09:07.000
It can be equal to over less than the policy term.

09:07.000 --> 09:16.000
Real-world example, SEMA buys a 20-year LIC policy but opts for a limited premium paying term of 10 years.

09:16.000 --> 09:25.000
This means she only needs to pay premiums for the first 10 years while the policy coverage continues for 20 years.

09:25.000 --> 09:34.000
This feature is useful for people who expect their income to reduce later in life or want to finish paying early.

09:34.000 --> 09:36.000
10. ADDB RIDER

09:36.000 --> 09:40.000
Accidental death and disability benefit rider

09:40.000 --> 09:50.000
ADDB rider provides an additional sum assured in case the life in short dies or becomes permanently disabled due to an accident.

09:50.000 --> 09:55.000
It's an optional rider that can be attached to many base LIC plans.

09:55.000 --> 10:07.000
Real-world example, imagine Rohit buys a policy with a base sum assured of 10 lakhs rupees and adds an ADDB rider for another 10 lakhs rupees.

10:07.000 --> 10:14.000
If he dies in an accident, his family will receive 20 lakhs rupees base plus ADDB.

10:14.000 --> 10:21.000
If he becomes permanently disabled, he may get the ADDB benefit in installments.

10:21.000 --> 10:33.000
This rider offers enhanced protection in unforeseen and unfortunate events especially useful for individuals in high-risk professions or frequent travelers.

10:33.000 --> 10:36.000
11. Accident Rider

10:36.000 --> 10:45.000
The accident rider provides an additional payout if the policy holder suffers death or sometimes specific injuries due to an accident.

10:45.000 --> 10:51.000
While similar to ADDB, this may be more limited in some policies.

10:51.000 --> 10:54.000
Real-world example

10:54.000 --> 11:07.000
If Mina has a life insurance policy with an accident rider and she dies in a road accident, her nominee will receive the base sum assured plus the accident rider benefit.

11:07.000 --> 11:12.000
This financial support can help the family cope with sudden losses.

11:12.000 --> 11:15.000
12. TURN INSURANCE RIDER

11:15.000 --> 11:24.000
Term rider is an add-on that allows the policy holder to enhance the sum assured for a limited term within the base policy.

11:24.000 --> 11:28.000
It is usually cheaper than buying a separate term policy.

11:28.000 --> 11:38.000
Real-world example, Amit has a policy of 10 lakhs rupees but adds a term rider of 15 lakhs rupees for 20 years.

11:38.000 --> 11:44.000
If he passes away within 20 years, his nominee gets 25 lakhs rupees.

11:44.000 --> 11:50.000
After 20 years, the rider ends and only base cover remains.

11:50.000 --> 11:54.000
13. Premium waiver benefit, PWB

11:54.000 --> 12:06.000
PWB ensures that if the premium pair, usually parent or proposer, dies or becomes disabled, all future premiums are waived and the policy continues as normal.

12:07.000 --> 12:13.000
Real-world example, Raj buys a child plan for his son with PWB.

12:13.000 --> 12:17.000
Unfortunately, Raj dies in an accident.

12:17.000 --> 12:26.000
Because of PWB, all future premiums are waived but the policy continues and his son will receive all maturity benefits.

12:26.000 --> 12:30.000
14. Critical Illness rider

12:30.000 --> 12:41.000
This rider offers a lump sum payout if the insured is diagnosed with a listed critical illness such as cancer, heart attack or kidney failure.

12:41.000 --> 12:51.000
Real-world example, if Shreya has a critical illness rider and is diagnosed with cancer, she will receive the rider some assured.

12:51.000 --> 12:57.000
This helps cover expensive treatments or compensate for income loss.

12:57.000 --> 12:59.000
15. Maturity

12:59.000 --> 13:08.000
Maturity refers to the date when the policy term ends and the insured receives the maturity amount including bonuses if applicable.

13:08.000 --> 13:13.000
Real-world example, Ravi took a 20 year endowment policy.

13:13.000 --> 13:22.000
After paying premiums for 20 years, the policy matures and he receives 5 lakhs rupees as maturity benefit.

13:22.000 --> 13:27.000
This helps fulfill his retirement or child education goals.

13:27.000 --> 13:30.000
16. Death Benefit

13:30.000 --> 13:37.000
The death benefit is the amount paid to the nominee if the insured person dies during the policy term.

13:37.000 --> 13:46.000
This may include the sum assured, accrued bonuses and any additional rider benefits depending on the plan.

13:46.000 --> 13:55.000
Real-world example, Manoj had a sum assured of 10 lakhs rupees and had accumulated bonuses of 3 lakhs rupees.

13:55.000 --> 14:02.000
Upon his death, his wife, the nominee received 13 lakhs rupees as the death benefit.

14:02.000 --> 14:09.000
This financial support helped her manage household expenses and children's education.

14:09.000 --> 14:11.000
17. Nominee

14:11.000 --> 14:19.000
A nominee is the person chosen by the policy holder to receive the benefits in case of the police holder's demise.

14:20.000 --> 14:25.000
A nominee can be a family member, child, spouse or even a trust.

14:25.000 --> 14:33.000
Real-world example, Rita took a life insurance policy and nominated her son Rohan as the nominee.

14:33.000 --> 14:43.000
In case of her unfortunate demise, LIC will pay the policy benefits directly to Rohan without any legal complications.

14:43.000 --> 14:45.000
18. Assigning

14:45.000 --> 14:52.000
An assignee is a person or institution to whom the rights of the policy are legally transferred.

14:52.000 --> 15:00.000
This usually happens when the policy is used as collateral for a loan or as part of a legal settlement.

15:00.000 --> 15:07.000
Real-world example, Ramesh needed a loan and pledged his LIC policy to the bank.

15:07.000 --> 15:10.000
He assigned the policy to the bank.

15:10.000 --> 15:18.000
If Ramesh fails to repay the loan, the bank can claim the policy proceeds up to the outstanding loan amount.

15:18.000 --> 15:20.000
19. Premium

15:20.000 --> 15:32.000
Premium is the amount paid by the policy holder to the insurance company at regular intervals monthly, quarterly, half yearly or yearly to keep the policy active.

15:33.000 --> 15:40.000
Real-world example, Neha pays 12,000 rupees per year towards her LIC endowment plan.

15:40.000 --> 15:43.000
This amount is her annual premium.

15:43.000 --> 15:47.000
If she doesn't pay this, the policy may lapse.

15:47.000 --> 15:49.000
20. Grace Period

15:49.000 --> 15:59.000
Grace Period is the extra time given after the premium due date during which the policy holder can still pay the premium without losing policy benefits.

16:00.000 --> 16:09.000
For most LIC policies, it's 30 days for yearly, half yearly, quarterly modes and 15 days for monthly mode.

16:09.000 --> 16:15.000
Real-world example, amidst premium due date was 10th March, but he forgot.

16:15.000 --> 16:18.000
He paid it on 5th April.

16:18.000 --> 16:25.000
Since he paid within the 30-day Grace Period, his policy remained active without penalty.

16:25.000 --> 16:28.000
21. Look in Period

16:28.000 --> 16:36.000
The look in or free look period is typically 15 days, 30 days for online policies.

16:36.000 --> 16:45.000
From the date of receiving the policy document, during which the policy holder can cancel the policy if not satisfied.

16:45.000 --> 16:52.000
Real-world example, Priya bought a policy online but changed her mind after reading the terms.

16:52.000 --> 16:59.000
She cancelled it within 30 days and received her premium back, minus minimal charges.

16:59.000 --> 17:12.000
